 The main issue is that you are trying to concatenate double values with strings using +. This will not work directly in Java.

Here is one way to fix it:

```java
static String toDecimalDegrees(double degrees) {

  double minutes = (degrees - (int)degrees) * 60;
  double seconds = (minutes - (int)minutes) * 60;

  // Use String.format to properly format the double values
  return String.format("%d° %02.0f' %02.2f\"", (int)degrees, minutes, seconds);

}
```

The key changes:

- Return type is String instead of double
- Use String.format() to format the degree, minutes, seconds
- Specify formatting like %02.0f to pad with zeros
- Surround with quotes and degrees symbol

This will properly concatenate the formatted double values into a string.

You can also build the string manually using Double.toString() if you prefer. But String.format() is a cleaner approach.

The key is that you can't directly concatenate doubles and strings with +. You need to convert the doubles to formatted strings first.

