how can I incorperate my output method?&gt;

 To incorporate the output method, you can call it after converting the coordinates in each case:

```java
// In main method

switch(choice) {

  case 1: 
    // Convert decimal to DMS
    toDMS(degrees);

    // Output result
    output();
    break;

  case 2:
    // Convert DMS to decimal 

    // Output result
    output();
    break;

}

// Output method
static void output() {
  // Print output message
  System.out.println("Conversion completed!"); 
}
```

Some ways you could use the output method:

- Print a message that the conversion is complete
- Print the converted coordinates 
- Format the output nicely (add labels, formatting, etc)
- Write the output to a file instead of printing 
- Clear the input after each conversion

The key is to call it after you've performed the conversion in each case. This keeps the conversion and output logic separated.

You can also call it multiple times, like after converting and again after printing the result.

This is a good use of methods to break the code into logical parts - get input, convert, output result.

this while loop is always true, how can I properly check the users input

                System.out.println(&quot;Enter Direction (N/S/E/W): &quot;);
                String direction = input.next();
                while(direction != &quot;N&quot; || direction!= &quot;S&quot; || direction!= &quot;E&quot; || direction!= &quot;W&quot;){
                    System.out.println(&quot;Enter Direction (N/S/E/W): &quot;);
                    System.out.println(direction);
                    direction = input.next();
                }

 The issue is that you are using || (OR) conditional logic in the while loop, which will always evaluate to true. 

To properly check that the input is one of the valid directions, you need to use && (AND) instead:

```java
System.out.print("Enter Direction (N/S/E/W): ");
String direction = input.next();

while(!(direction.equals("N") || 
       direction.equals("S") ||
       direction.equals("E") ||
       direction.equals("W"))) {

  System.out.print("Invalid direction. Enter N, S, E or W: ");
  direction = input.next();

}
```

This checks that the input is NOT equal to any of the valid options using ! and ||. 

The loop will continue prompting until the input matches one of the directions.

Another approach is:

```java 
while(!direction.matches("[NSEW]")) {
  // prompt for input again
}
```

Using .matches() and a regex to check the input is one of N, S, E or W.

The key thing is to use AND/OR logical operators carefully to get the desired conditional check.
